@MarkusH 

It does work for your purpose, yes. But it will only work with one very specific configuration, albeit a very popular one: using scp to transfer files to web server.

Consider there are another way of transferring files: FTP, SFTP, FTPS, WebDAV, CIFS. And consider something like application servers running from read only filesystem, serving files from remote databases.

For WhiteNoise v2.0+, this needs to be modified slightly, so that it works with [autorefresh](http://whitenoise.evans.io/en/latest/base.html#autorefresh) when developing. (Feature was added in https://github.com/evansd/whitenoise/commit/25f5757b41f5d876252dff873ecb88b177793a3e).

eg:

```python
from whitenoise.django import DjangoWhiteNoise


class IndexWhiteNoise(DjangoWhiteNoise):

    INDEX_NAME = 'index.html'

    def add_files(self, *args, **kwargs):
        super(IndexWhiteNoise, self).add_files(*args, **kwargs)
        index_page_suffix = "/" + self.INDEX_NAME
        index_name_length = len(self.INDEX_NAME)
        index_files = {}
        for url, static_file in self.files.items():
            # Add an additional fake filename to serve index pages for '/'.
            if url.endswith(index_page_suffix):
                index_files[url[:-index_name_length]] = static_file
        self.files.update(index_files)

    def find_file(self, url):
        # In debug mode, find_file() is used to serve files directly from the filesystem
        # instead of using the list in `self.files`, so we append the index filename so
        # that will be served if present.
        if url[-1] == '/':
            url += self.INDEX_NAME
        return super(CustomWhiteNoise, self).find_file(url)
```

