@ecdsa I initially was doing a hash160 - i.e. ripemd160(sha256(x)).

This turns out to be a little expensive - it was slower than parsing the scripts in Python.
So I'm now trying ripemd160 only.  But it made me think - isn't 160 bits overkill?  Can we not take 96 or 128 bits and use that as our hash for our purposes?  Collisions are still vanishingly unlikely given our data set size (which is nothing like 2^48 in size), but dropping to 96 or even 128 bits would reduce memory consumption and DB size.  We could take the first N bits of the ripemd160.  N can be anything that's a multiple of 8.

