Ok. So if I get it, it doesn't work because there is no threadpool to defer to in the StubTreq's in-memory reactor, does it? I "fixed" it by taking a different codepath for testing like so:  

```python
def test_func():
  return({'response':'hi'})


class HTTPApplication(object):
    app = Klein()

    def __init__(self, testing=False):
        self._testing=testing
        reactor.suggestThreadPoolSize(5)

    @app.route("/test", methods=['GET'])
    @inlineCallbacks
    def test(self, request):
        if request.method.decode('utf-8', 'strict') == 'GET':     
            request.setHeader('Content-Type', 'application/json')
            try:
                response = yield test_func() if self._testing
                           else threads.deferToThread(test_func)
                returnValue(json.dumps(response))
            except:
                request.setResponseCode(404)
                returnValue(json.dumps({"error": "async failure"}))


if __name__ == '__main__':   
    http_app = HTTPApplication(testing=True)
    stub = StubTreq(http_app.app.resource())

    # The response is still NOT_DONE_YET
    @inlineCallbacks
    def parse_test(treq):
        response = yield treq.request(method='GET', url='http://localhost/test')
        treq.flush()
        returnValue(response)

    print(parse_test(stub).code)
```

Taking different codepaths doesn't make me very happy as it means taking the risk of doing pointless testing but I think this may be acceptable in this case. Still there may be a better fix for this one.
And yes this is just a dummy example to emphasize my issue 😉 

