```
import chardet

def ensure_text_type(value):
    if isinstance(value, text_type):
        encoding = 'utf-8'
    else:
        encoding = chardet.detect(value).get('encoding') or 'utf-8'
    return value.decode(encoding) if hasattr(value, 'decode') else value
```

As discussed in other issues/PRs and mulled over on my own I believe the correct thing to do is not to have the root environment on the user's path. I instead believe that the correct thing to do is to introduce a `sbin` directory under the conda directory. The path to conda's `sbin` or similar must always be on the user's `PATH`. This `sbin` will only include the bare minimum conda tools that are necessary for any basic conda functions (this would predominantly be the `activate`/`deactivate` scripts).

@mingwandroid As a general good practice for OS/shell agnostic tools, I see little value in making different shells behave differently (whether for good vs bad OSes or good vs bad shells). This adds both a confusion on the user's side where different documentation is necessary for different people but also drastically complicates long-term support for code when code that is intended to mirror each other no longer does so. Further I do think the `sbin` idea will address most real concerns with forcing some conda directory onto the user's `PATH`.

@wulmer The main reason I was forced to leave root on the PATH is because certain shells are simply unable to detect script locations when sourced and hence I would have no way to detect the root path (unless we introduced some new environment variable like `CONDA_ROOT`). I feel like the `sbin` concept would address your concerns.

